Comment: E4, as everybody knows, is the very popular move to start out the chess game. I bet at least 60% of games start with e4. But the most questionable is how to respond to this. There are exactly 20 ways. Some people respond what I call traditionally; e5. But there are other ways that work better for some. He responded c6.
My guess already is that he will develop mostly on the Queenside. Rated 1822 on the game database, it looks like it will work quite fine.
That was very strong. He simply took over the center in a "piece developing" way.
That was very strong. He simply took over the center in a "piece developing" way.
What I say, is that this is way too defensive for the 3rd move. It sets up a fairly good opening though.
"Some ways work better for some" as I said on move 1. I Responded the way I would to it. I knew this position would come ever since I did the questionable move, d3.

This has one or two bad points to it, but I think it is better than the alternative, dxe4. That would sooner make an open file in the center and would leave me with either Nxd1 or Kxd1. Both I don't like. Kastling is a total option. But basically, I did a Caro-Kann opening. An average one.
This was not one common response. I just thought I could put some pressure through the hole. I was thinking of rather doing Qf3.
